Task A: Iris Data¶

Perform K-Means clustering on the dataset, iris.csv (from the UCI Machine Learning Repository). Before using the data for clustering, you might have to remove a few columns because the K-Means algorithm involves the calculation of Euclidian distance. You can choose various values of K; however, you must also choose K = 3 in this case. Upon clustering at K = 3, check how much similar your three clusters are as compared to the labels of species setosa, versicolour, and verginic

In [21]:
iris_features = iris.drop(columns=['species'])

kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=3, random_state=0)
kmeans.fit(iris_features)

cluster_labels = kmeans.labels_

iris['cluster'] = cluster_labels

species_mode = iris.groupby('cluster')['species'].apply(lambda x: x.mode().iloc[0]).to_dict()

iris['cluster_species'] = iris['cluster'].map(species_mode)

conf_matrix = confusion_matrix(iris['species'], iris['cluster_species'])

sns.heatmap(conf_matrix, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Blues',
            xticklabels=np.unique(iris['cluster_species']),
            yticklabels=np.unique(iris['species']))
plt.xlabel('Cluster')
plt.ylabel('Actual Species')
plt.title('Confusion Matrix for K-Means Clustering (K=3)')
plt.show()

Iris Data Conclusion¶

The K-means clustering in the confusion matrix above shows the various groupings based on feature. It shows a solid separation of the "Setosa" along with some overlap of the "Versicolor" and "Virginia" which suggests they have similar features, this overall showing that the K-Means has identified the overlaps in the data.

In [22]:
wine_features = wine.drop(columns=['Wine'])

kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=3, random_state=0)
kmeans.fit(wine_features)

cluster_labels = kmeans.labels_

wine['cluster'] = cluster_labels

wine_mode = wine.groupby('cluster')['Wine'].apply(lambda x: x.mode().iloc[0]).to_dict()

wine['cluster_wine'] = wine['cluster'].map(wine_mode)

conf_matrix = confusion_matrix(wine['Wine'], wine['cluster_wine'])

sns.heatmap(conf_matrix, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Blues',
            xticklabels=np.unique(wine['cluster_wine']),
            yticklabels=np.unique(wine['Wine']))
plt.xlabel('Predicted Cluster')
plt.ylabel('Actual Wine')
plt.title('Confusion Matrix for K-Means Clustering (K=3)')
plt.show()

Wine Data Conclusion¶

The matrix above shows that the wine has good spearation in the wine but also having some overlap in the different types of wine. Similar to Iris the k-means identified the groups in the wine dataset.

weather = weather.drop(columns=['RainToday', 'RainTomorrow'])

# Handle missing values by filling them with the mean of the column
weather = weather.fillna(weather.mean())

# Display the first few rows of the preprocessed dataset
print(weather.head())

# Function to perform K-Means clustering and return cluster labels
def kmeans_clustering(data, n_clusters):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=n_clusters, random_state=0)
    kmeans.fit(data)
    return kmeans.labels_

# Range of K values
k_values = range(2, 7)

# Dictionary to store cluster labels for different K values
cluster_labels_dict = {}

for k in k_values:
    cluster_labels_dict[k] = kmeans_clustering(weather, k)

# Display cluster labels for K=3 as an example
print(cluster_labels_dict[3])

# Function to plot the clusters
def plot_clusters(data, labels, k):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    sns.scatterplot(x=data['MinTemp'], y=data['MaxTemp'], hue=labels, palette='viridis')
    plt.title(f'K-Means Clustering with K={k}')
    plt.xlabel('MinTemp')
    plt.ylabel('MaxTemp')
    plt.legend(title='Cluster')
    plt.show()

# Plot clusters for K=2 to K=6
for k in k_values:
    plot_clusters(weather, cluster_labels_dict[k], k)

WeatherAUS Data Conclusion¶

The 2 to 6 k-means clustering shows a broard range of patterns between max and min temprature, the right amount of clusters is 3-4 in this case since too many can lead to overfitting in this case when you get into 5-6 but 2 clusters can seem too small of an ammount. Therefore 3-4 provides the right amount of granularity where more clusters have too much overlap.
